\subsection{Performance on synthetic out-of-distribution data}
To quantitatively evaluate the model's ability to distinguish In-Distribution (InD) and OoD samples, we first tested it on a synthetic validation set. For this test, OoD maps were created by applying a 1.3x rescaling to the noiseless convergence signal of a held-out set of maps, mimicking a significant deviation in baryonic effects. We assess performance using the partial Area Under the Curve (AUC) of the Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) curve, focusing on the stringent False Positive Rate (FPR) regime of $[0.001, 0.05]$ where high-confidence detections are critical.

Our method achieves a partial AUC of 0.2223 on this task. For context, a random classifier would yield a score of approximately 0.05 in this FPR range. This result demonstrates a strong capability to identify anomalous maps with high confidence. The full partial ROC curve, shown in Figure \ref{fig:image1}, illustrates this performance. The curve rises sharply within the shaded scoring region, indicating that the highest Negative Log-Likelihood (NLL) scores are almost exclusively assigned to the synthetically generated OoD samples. This confirms that the model effectively separates the two populations, maintaining a high True Positive Rate (TPR) while incurring a very low rate of false alarms. This successful validation provides confidence in applying the trained model to the blind test set.

