    \label{fig:image1}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Anomaly scores on the test set}
We then applied the full inference pipeline to the 10,000 maps in the blind test set. For each map, we computed an OoD score defined as the NLL evaluated using the parameters $\hat{\theta}$ predicted by the MLP regressor: $\text{OoD Score} = - \log p(\mathbf{x}_{\text{WST}} | \hat{\theta})$. The resulting distribution of these scores is presented in Figure \ref{fig:image0}.

The histogram shows a primary distribution centered at a median NLL of 87.36, which is consistent with the validation NLL achieved during training (82.1762) and represents the InD samples that are well-described by our model. Critically, the distribution exhibits a pronounced, heavy tail extending to extremely high NLL values, with a maximum score of 492,662. As validated by our synthetic data experiment, this long tail corresponds to a distinct population of maps whose structural features are assigned an exceptionally low probability by our conditional model. These samples are therefore identified as strong OoD candidates, whose features are fundamentally inconsistent with the learned distribution of the fiducial simulation, even after accounting for variations in the five known physical parameters.

